are complex valued fields.

01:33:45.180 --> 01:33:50.120
So each field is not a number at each point in space, but a complex number at each point

01:33:50.120 --> 01:33:51.380
in space.

01:33:51.380 --> 01:33:54.580
So this is all to say, don't be intimidated.

01:33:54.580 --> 01:34:01.280
When you hear people say, the standard model of particle physics has a gauge group SU2 cross

01:34:01.280 --> 01:34:02.720
U1.

01:34:02.720 --> 01:34:07.780
That's just a way of saying there are three fields that are complex valued that get rotated

01:34:07.780 --> 01:34:09.620
into each other.

01:34:09.620 --> 01:34:13.280
There's a separate set of two fields that are also complex valued that get rotated into

01:34:13.280 --> 01:34:14.280
each other.

01:34:14.280 --> 01:34:15.640
That's SU2.

01:34:15.640 --> 01:34:21.980
And then you could have a single complex valued field that can still in some sense rotate

01:34:21.980 --> 01:34:27.540
into itself because a complex valued field has a real part and an imaginary part.

01:34:27.540 --> 01:34:30.820
There is something called the complex plane where we have a complex number.

01:34:30.840 --> 01:34:36.160
We write the real value of the number on the horizontal axis, the imaginary value on the

01:34:36.160 --> 01:34:37.160
vertical axis.

01:34:37.160 --> 01:34:42.280
Well, you can rotate the complex plane, and that rotation is called U1.

01:34:42.280 --> 01:34:49.400
So these are all just fancy ways of talking about rotating fields into each other.

01:34:49.400 --> 01:34:50.560
And it doesn't matter.

01:34:50.560 --> 01:34:55.760
It doesn't matter what rotation you do, the same physical predictions will be made.

01:34:55.760 --> 01:34:57.560
That's what makes it asymmetry.

01:34:57.900 --> 01:35:03.140
Indeed, this idea of having three fields that we rotate into each other is a very simple

01:35:03.140 --> 01:35:04.140
example.

01:35:04.140 --> 01:35:05.140
They are called quarks.

01:35:05.140 --> 01:35:06.140
Okay.

01:35:06.140 --> 01:35:09.460
You may have heard that quarks come in three colors.

01:35:09.460 --> 01:35:13.580
There are red quarks, green quarks, and blue quarks.

01:35:13.580 --> 01:35:14.860
That's not quite right.

01:35:14.860 --> 01:35:18.180
Like so many things that you've been told.

01:35:18.180 --> 01:35:22.260
You've been told something that is not quite right, but good enough.

01:35:22.260 --> 01:35:24.100
And now you're ready for the real stuff.

01:35:24.100 --> 01:35:29.360
The real stuff is not that there are three different quarks, but there is a three-dimensional

01:35:29.360 --> 01:35:32.160
space of quarks.

01:35:32.160 --> 01:35:36.440
So the subtle difference I'm pointing to here is it's not that there are red quarks,

01:35:36.440 --> 01:35:38.280
green quarks, and blue quarks.

01:35:38.280 --> 01:35:43.920
There are quarks that every quark, I should say, should be thought of as a combination

01:35:43.920 --> 01:35:47.480
of a bit of red, a bit of green, and a bit of blue.

01:35:47.480 --> 01:35:48.640
And you can choose.

01:35:48.640 --> 01:35:50.320
You can rotate your axes.

01:35:50.320 --> 01:35:52.880
So you define what you mean by red, green, or blue.

01:35:52.900 --> 01:35:54.900
There's no actual reality to it.

01:35:54.900 --> 01:35:56.380
It has nothing to do with the real colors.

01:35:56.380 --> 01:35:57.380
Okay.

01:35:57.380 --> 01:36:00.060
You're not looking at a blue quark and it looks blue or anything like that.

01:36:00.060 --> 01:36:01.860
This is just a label.

01:36:01.860 --> 01:36:05.300
R, G, and B are completely equivalent to each other.

01:36:05.300 --> 01:36:09.220
These three-dimensional vector space of quark colors.

01:36:09.220 --> 01:36:14.140
And the real statement is not there are three different colors of quarks, but that quarks,

01:36:14.140 --> 01:36:19.420
every quark field is an element at every point in space of this three-dimensional, three-complex

01:36:19.420 --> 01:36:22.260
dimensional, I should say, vector space.

01:36:22.260 --> 01:36:30.880
There is an SU3 symmetry rotating the red, green, and blue axes into each other.

01:36:30.880 --> 01:36:32.200
Three different kinds of quarks.

01:36:32.200 --> 01:36:34.040
We conventionally labeled them by color.

01:36:34.040 --> 01:36:37.280
There's a symmetry where we can rotate them into each other, SU3.

01:36:37.280 --> 01:36:38.280
Very, very nice.

01:36:38.280 --> 01:36:42.000
And then we'll talk about in the book what that means, SU3, et cetera, et cetera, how

01:36:42.000 --> 01:36:43.000
to implement it.

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:44.000
Great.

01:36:44.000 --> 01:36:45.640
So what?

01:36:45.640 --> 01:36:47.200
What difference does that make, really?

01:36:47.220 --> 01:36:52.020
Well, you instantly know there is a conserved quantity, because there is a symmetry.

01:36:52.020 --> 01:36:55.820
In Neurthus Theorem tells you there's always a conserved quantity when there's a symmetry.

01:36:55.820 --> 01:37:00.700
So that's nice, but it isn't quite the punch line.

01:37:00.700 --> 01:37:02.420
The punch line comes from this.

01:37:02.420 --> 01:37:05.720
Let's imagine we have an even better symmetry.

01:37:05.720 --> 01:37:11.100
So we have these three fields we can rotate into each other, call that rotation SU3.

01:37:11.100 --> 01:37:12.260
That's nice.

01:37:12.280 --> 01:37:18.840
But what if I want to rotate the axes of my red, green, blue space in one way at some

01:37:18.840 --> 01:37:23.240
point and in a completely different way at some other point?

01:37:23.240 --> 01:37:25.040
I didn't say that I could do that.

01:37:25.040 --> 01:37:28.040
I'm just asking whether it would be possible.

01:37:28.040 --> 01:37:33.280
So there is something called a global symmetry transformation where we take what we've defined

01:37:33.280 --> 01:37:40.000
to be red, green, and blue, and we rotate them everywhere all at once in some particular

01:37:40.000 --> 01:37:41.000
way.

01:37:41.020 --> 01:37:45.020
It's a global transformation of what we mean by red, green, and blue.

01:37:45.020 --> 01:37:46.020
That's fine.

01:37:46.020 --> 01:37:48.900
No one really is bothered by that.

01:37:48.900 --> 01:37:55.060
But if you want, if you have the aspiration of saying, I would like to separately define

01:37:55.060 --> 01:38:02.260
what I mean by red, green, and blue independently at every point in space, can I do that?

01:38:02.260 --> 01:38:07.740
That would be an enormously bigger symmetry, because I'm separately able to define what

01:38:07.740 --> 01:38:10.980
I mean by red, green, and blue all throughout space.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:13.760
That's a lot going on.

01:38:13.760 --> 01:38:18.880
And the answer is you can do that, but you have to sort of figure, you have to make sure

01:38:18.880 --> 01:38:22.120
that you're allowed to, that it's a well-defined thing.

01:38:22.120 --> 01:38:26.240
Because whether we call a quark at any one point in space a quark field, whether we call

01:38:26.240 --> 01:38:31.640
it red, green, or blue, or some combination thereof, that's completely arbitrary, right?

01:38:31.640 --> 01:38:33.520
That makes no physical difference.

01:38:33.520 --> 01:38:39.280
But if we have two different points in space, and we have the same quark field, remember

01:38:39.280 --> 01:38:43.460
the quark field will take values at every point in space.

01:38:43.460 --> 01:38:45.540
And let's ask the following question.

01:38:45.540 --> 01:38:50.380
At these two different points in space, does the quark field have the same color?

01:38:50.380 --> 01:38:51.900
Or does it have some different colors?

01:38:51.900 --> 01:38:54.340
Is it rotated by 90 degrees or whatever?

01:38:54.340 --> 01:38:56.300
That should be a well-defined question, right?

01:38:56.300 --> 01:38:58.780
Is it the same color or a different color?

01:38:58.780 --> 01:39:04.260
Well, if I'm allowed to rotate my axes separately at every point in space, it seems like I can't

01:39:04.280 --> 01:39:09.560
answer that question, because I could have some quark field that I am just simply defining

01:39:09.560 --> 01:39:15.760
to be red at one point in space by appropriately rotating my little red, green, blue axes.

01:39:15.760 --> 01:39:19.760
And again, these axes are completely imaginary, like not imaginary in the imaginary number

01:39:19.760 --> 01:39:21.280
sense, but conceptual.

01:39:21.280 --> 01:39:25.320
They're not axes of literal space, they're in quark space, okay?

01:39:25.320 --> 01:39:29.320
There's three different directions the quark field can be vibrating, the red direction,

01:39:29.320 --> 01:39:31.960
the green direction, the blue direction.

01:39:31.980 --> 01:39:36.340
And likewise, okay, so I have a red quark at one point in space, and I rotate my axes

01:39:36.340 --> 01:39:40.340
so that at some other point in space, it's also a red quark.

01:39:40.340 --> 01:39:41.340
But is that legit?

01:39:41.340 --> 01:39:45.540
I mean, I could have rotated it, so it was a blue quark, and there's a physical difference

01:39:45.540 --> 01:39:46.540
there.

01:39:46.540 --> 01:39:53.340
So what I'm getting at is, if you want to be able to have this mega-symmetry that lets

01:39:53.340 --> 01:40:00.060
you rotate in red, green, blue space independently at every point in space, you also need some

01:40:00.080 --> 01:40:02.240
way to compare.

01:40:02.240 --> 01:40:06.720
You need some way to answer the question, what is the value, let's put it this way,

01:40:06.720 --> 01:40:13.360
how does the value of the color of the quark change as I travel along some path, okay?

01:40:13.360 --> 01:40:19.720
I can connect these two points in space with some path, and I can ask how the axes that

01:40:19.720 --> 01:40:24.080
define red, green, and blue are changing as I move down the path.

01:40:24.080 --> 01:40:28.440
So I need some information that lets me answer that question.

01:40:28.460 --> 01:40:31.220
How do these axes change as I go down the path?

01:40:31.220 --> 01:40:34.940
How does the definition of red, green, and blue change?

01:40:34.940 --> 01:40:39.500
It's not a rigid structure like it would have been if I just had that global symmetry.

01:40:39.500 --> 01:40:44.500
Now I'm able to change what I mean by red, green, and blue independently everywhere.

01:40:44.500 --> 01:40:48.540
Something needs to absorb the information of how I did that.

01:40:48.540 --> 01:40:49.540
What would do that?

01:40:49.540 --> 01:40:53.500
What would carry that information about how I defined red, green, and blue at every point

01:40:53.500 --> 01:40:54.700
in space?

01:40:54.700 --> 01:40:57.140
The answer is a field.

01:40:57.160 --> 01:40:58.560
I need another kind of field.

01:40:58.560 --> 01:40:59.880
I already have the quark field.

01:40:59.880 --> 01:41:03.720
In fact, I have this sort of three different kinds of quark field, the red, green, and

01:41:03.720 --> 01:41:06.680
blue, three different directions in which the quark can rotate.

01:41:06.680 --> 01:41:13.080
But now I need an entirely new kind of field to carry the information that tells me how

01:41:13.080 --> 01:41:18.680
to relate the red, green, and blue axes at different points in space.

01:41:18.680 --> 01:41:20.960
And the mathematicians know how to do this.

01:41:20.960 --> 01:41:26.360
This is called a connection field, and the mathematical subject that studies these things

01:41:26.420 --> 01:41:27.820
is called fiber bundles.

01:41:27.820 --> 01:41:31.900
It's a subject within differential geometry.

01:41:31.900 --> 01:41:32.820
You can read all about it.

01:41:32.820 --> 01:41:35.540
Again, we're not going to go into all those details.

01:41:35.540 --> 01:41:39.780
But the point, and this is a big point, and it's another one of those miraculous points

01:41:39.780 --> 01:41:46.340
that is very, very important, is that you can do these independent symmetry transformations

01:41:46.340 --> 01:41:51.700
at different points, but only if you introduce a new field that lets you keep track of the

01:41:51.700 --> 01:41:55.700
information relating what's going on at different points.

01:41:55.800 --> 01:42:01.160
So these symmetries that can happen independently at every different point are called gauge

01:42:01.160 --> 01:42:06.520
symmetries, or simply local symmetries in contrast with the global symmetries that

01:42:06.520 --> 01:42:07.880
we were talking about.

01:42:07.880 --> 01:42:14.760
To start, gauge symmetries, unlike global symmetries, come along with the new field,

01:42:14.760 --> 01:42:17.400
the gauge field, aka the connection.

01:42:17.400 --> 01:42:21.400
Those are the same thing, the gauge field, the connection field, the field that keeps

01:42:21.420 --> 01:42:26.860
track of how your axes are changing from point to point in space, okay?

01:42:26.860 --> 01:42:32.740
It's much like in space time, if you go back to book one of the biggest ideas, in space

01:42:32.740 --> 01:42:37.780
time, just to compare the question, what direction is a vector pointing in?

01:42:37.780 --> 01:42:41.420
You need to be able to parallel transport vectors from one point to another, and you

01:42:41.420 --> 01:42:43.660
need a connection field to be able to do that.

01:42:43.660 --> 01:42:47.180
That connection depends on the metric, in general relativity.

01:42:47.180 --> 01:42:50.300
Here, in gauge theories of particle physics, there's no metric.

01:42:50.360 --> 01:42:52.400
There just is the connection.

01:42:52.400 --> 01:42:55.280
That's a field that shows up as the gauge field.

01:42:55.280 --> 01:42:58.080
And so, what does that field do?

01:42:58.080 --> 01:42:59.320
What are its dynamics?

01:42:59.320 --> 01:43:00.320
How does it behave?

01:43:00.320 --> 01:43:02.040
How does it interact with other fields?

01:43:02.040 --> 01:43:03.720
There's a whole bunch of questions.

01:43:03.720 --> 01:43:06.920
You're going to read the book, so you're going to know the answer to these questions.

01:43:06.920 --> 01:43:14.720
But the punchline is that field, that connection field, you need to implement the gauge symmetry

01:43:14.720 --> 01:43:16.640
is the force field.

01:43:16.660 --> 01:43:22.980
It is the electromagnetic field for electromagnetism, or the gravitational field for gravity.

01:43:22.980 --> 01:43:28.740
And it gives rise to particles, photons for electromagnetism, gravitons for gravity.

01:43:28.740 --> 01:43:33.020
And there's also the nuclear forces, the strong and weak nuclear forces.

01:43:33.020 --> 01:43:37.620
Mathematically, they are boson fields, and you can derive that.

01:43:37.620 --> 01:43:43.820
And there are interactions with other fields, the way that the force carrying fields interact

01:43:43.840 --> 01:43:49.160
with the non-force carrying fields, the electrons and neutrinos and quarks and so forth, is entirely

01:43:49.160 --> 01:43:53.440
determined by the demands of this symmetry, okay?

01:43:53.440 --> 01:43:58.120
Given the fact that you want this symmetry to exist, not only do you need this gauge

01:43:58.120 --> 01:44:02.440
field, but you know how the gauge field interacts with other fields.

01:44:02.440 --> 01:44:04.840
And you know more than that, the symmetry is super powerful.

01:44:04.840 --> 01:44:08.920
This is why physicists sort of start jumping up and down when they talk about symmetry.

01:44:08.920 --> 01:44:12.840
They get very excited, because it really is a very powerful concept.

01:44:12.840 --> 01:44:19.500
You can derive features of the dynamics of the gauge fields all by itself.

01:44:19.500 --> 01:44:23.980
So in particular, there's one very, very important feature that kind of puzzled people for a

01:44:23.980 --> 01:44:24.980
long time.

01:44:24.980 --> 01:44:27.100
Let me back up to just mention.

01:44:27.100 --> 01:44:31.580
The idea of a gauge field was kind of understood by Maxwell.

01:44:31.580 --> 01:44:35.540
He understood that his electric field and magnetic field could be derived from a more

01:44:35.540 --> 01:44:40.020
fundamental single thing that we would now call the gauge field.

01:44:40.020 --> 01:44:47.080
It wasn't until the 1950s that Yang and Mills suggested generalizing this idea of the electromagnetic

01:44:47.080 --> 01:44:51.040
gauge field to more complicated gauge fields, SU2, SU3, etc.

01:44:51.040 --> 01:44:55.760
And it took a while, it took until the 70s, really, for us to figure out how to make that

01:44:55.760 --> 01:44:57.720
happen, okay?

01:44:57.720 --> 01:45:02.800
But it turns out that that symmetry, this SU2 or SU3 symmetry or whatever it is, has

01:45:02.800 --> 01:45:08.120
